eader":"His electric shocks could restart a stopped heart","body":"Working at Johns Hopkins in the early 1930s, he showed that a properly graduated electric shock could restore the rhythm of a fibrillating heart — the experimental basis of modern cardiac defibrillation. Alone or with collaborators he published more than forty papers on the circulation."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Edited the physiology journal thirty-two years, mostly unpaid","body":"He served as managing editor of the American Journal of Physiology for thirty-two years, much of it without pay. He made the journal self-supporting and in 1921 helped found its companion, Physiological Reviews."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"donald-hooker-1876"},"I01359":{"id":"I01359","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"first_name":"Edith","middle_name":"Houghton","last_name":"Hooker","maiden_name":"Houghton","married_names":["Hooker"],"gender":"female","display_name":"Edith Houghton Hooker","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780502587/edithhoughton_h0zpmb.png"},"birth":{"year":1879,"month":12,"day":29,"city":"Buffalo","county":"Erie","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1948,"month":10,"day":23,"city":"Baltimore","state":"Maryland","country":"United States"},"residence":{},"burial":{},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":true,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":0,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["social_reform"],"notable_blurb":"Maryland suffrage leader and social reformer","primary_url":"https://msa.maryland.gov/msa/educ/exhibits/womenshallfame/html/hooker.html","primary_url_label":"Maryland Women's Hall of Fame"},"parents":{"father_name":"Alfred Augustus Houghton","mother_name":"Caroline Garlinghouse"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H04422","date_year":1905,"date_month":6,"date_day":14,"location_city":"Baltimore","location_state":"Maryland","location_country":"United States","children_ids":["HD5619","HD5620","HD5621","HD5622","HD5623"]}],"education":[{"school_name":"Bryn Mawr College","dates":"1901","type":"undergraduate","notes":"A.B."},{"institution_id":"INST146","type":"medical","notes":"left before finishing"}],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST146","relationship":"alumnus","institution_blurb":"Among the first women at Johns Hopkins Medical School; left to marry and pursue reform."}],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["suffragist","womens_rights","womens_hall_of_fame"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"I00170","display_label":"was also a prominent suffrage leader who married a Hooker","link_text":"Isabella Beecher Hooker"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"social_reform","header":"Took suffrage to the streets by automobile","body":"She founded Maryland's Just Government League in 1909 and its weekly Maryland Suffrage News in 1912, then carried the cause across the state in open-air meetings held from an automobile. In 1917 she became editor of The Suffragist, the National Woman's Party paper."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Her sister was Katharine Hepburn's mother","body":"Edith and her older sister Katharine Houghton Hepburn were both prominent leaders of the woman-suffrage movement; that sister's daughter was the actress Katharine Hepburn, making Edith the actress's aunt. The Houghton sisters were raised by freethinking parents who championed women's education."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Left Johns Hopkins medicine for a reformer's life","body":"One of the first women admitted to 